      explanation: `## Pathophysiology by Class

### Cnidarian Envenomation
- Nematocyst discharge on contact
- Pore-forming toxins
- Phospholipases
- Local tissue injury
- Rare systemic: Irukandji syndrome, cardiac toxicity

### Fish Envenomation
- Spine-based venom delivery
- Heat-labile proteins
- Severe local pain
- Tissue necrosis variable

### Echinoderm Envenomation
- Sea urchin spines with toxin glands
- Mechanical injury plus envenomation
- Granulomatous reaction to retained spines

## Treatment by Type

### Jellyfish
- Vinegar for box jellyfish (may worsen some species)
- Remove tentacles (protect hands)
- Hot water 45C for pain
- Antihistamines, analgesics

### Stingray
- Hot water immersion (45-50C)
- Wound exploration
- Imaging for retained barb
- Antibiotics if infection risk

### Sea Urchins
- Remove visible spines
- Hot water immersion
- Deep spines: may leave to resorb
- Surgical removal if joint involvement`,
