      explanation: `## Detailed Pathophysiology

### Cnidarian Toxins
- Pore-forming: cell membrane disruption
- Phospholipases: membrane breakdown
- Proteases: tissue destruction
- Cardiotoxins: box jellyfish (Chironex)
- Catecholamine release: Irukandji

### Irukandji Syndrome
- Carukia barnesi and others
- Minimal local symptoms
- Delayed severe systemic symptoms
- Catecholamine surge
- Hypertension, cardiac injury
- Pulmonary edema possible

### Fish Venom Toxicology
- Large proteins (heat-labile)
- Local pain mechanism: unknown
- Cytotoxic effects
- Minimal systemic effects usually

## Evidence-Based Management

### Cnidarian
- Decontamination: seawater rinse, vinegar (box jellyfish)
- Tentacle removal: scraping or forceps
- Pain: hot water, analgesia
- Severe: supportive, antivenom (Chironex)

### Fish/Echinoderm
- Hot water immersion: 45-50C for 30-90 min
- Wound care
- Imaging for foreign body
- Surgical exploration if deep/joint

### Antibiotic Indications
- Delayed presentation
- Deep puncture
- Immunocompromised
- Cover: Vibrio species`,
